Redeemed Britannia wrote:
Aikoland wrote:Then you have the dipshits like me who have a whole wiki for her (main) nation because reasons.

I've tried to transport my factbooks into iiwiki but couldn't figure out the way it works -never worked with wikipedia and all that- so I have a lot of respect for IIwiki posters tbh.

I am using iiwiki for an RP and it is kinda silly in my experience. One of the RP mods keeps editing my code spaghetti (not that I dislike that fact, he's just better than I am at this whole wiki thing) and you have to directly upload files to their site if you want images. Though, the latter is a kinda cool feature because it does allow more features than NS (I.E Uploading .svg files, releasing "updated" versions of a file, etc.)

At the end of the day though, iiwiki is very... restrictive in what you can do. You really can't make a narrative nation or even a synne-esc nation with iiwiki and there's a much higher standard of what is "acceptable." Not in the sense that you'd be instantly banned for posting an edgy dictator, but more in the sense that I probably couldn't post something like Wexas' vassal factbook.

by Kiu Ghesik » Fri Oct 01, 2021 6:16 am

Socialist Macronesia wrote:Personally, character wise, I used to like to strike a balance between unimportant characters and important characters but now I personally like writing ordinary people more than I do the most well-known people in the nation. Or, if they are well known, I like to write them as somewhat humble and down-to-earth people, and considering the history of Macronesia, that's probably a true characterization. Readers can empathize more with ordinary people than presidents, dictators, and royalty, and so they are better liked. Furthermore, when all you do is write about the most important people in your nation, you don't get a full view of what the nation is like. For example, if you solely read Ross's factbook, you may get the impression that he's not entirely a terrible guy, but if you read through the history, other characters' files, and the CNIF history, you may come to a different conclusion. If I'd settled for just writing Ross's factbook, none of those outside views would even exist, and people's impression of him would be much different. The same idea applies to other leaders I see. When they're portrayed solely from a point of view that chooses to make them look like they're in the right, I feel the need to question what they did wrong. And believe me, everybody's done something wrong, influential individuals moreso.

yee, honestly writing just leaders can get tedious. they just... come off as totally boring after a while, "oh look it's another character who controls things and has influence" and sometimes i just wanna write a girl trying to live life without fucking up all too badly in the process. rol it comes off as a breath of fresh air, honestly. it certainly managed to break my all-pervasive writer's block for a while, at least.
